restrictions: Most of the data stem from surveys. They reveal an overall picture of the Swiss municipalities. Thus, do not refer to specific municipalities to avoid misinterpretation and to avoid the revelation of the identity of our respondents. The data may only be used for research purposes. Beyond that, evaluations and analyses are only to be carried out in aggregated form. The confidentiality and anonymity of the provided information has been guaranteed to all the participants in the survey. For this reason, conducting and publishing individual municipal data is explicitely not permitted. In case of questions or uncertainties, please do contact the owner (see above).
citationRequirements: Ladner, Andreas; Steiner, Reto; Haus, Alexander; Kaiser, Claire; Keuffer, Nicolas; Bernier, Ada; Reichmuth, Lukas (2021): Schweizer Gemeindemonitoring 1998 bis 2017 (Datensatz). Université de Lausanne, Institut de hautes études en administration publique (IDHEAP).
conditions: for details such as survey implementation, survey content, data quality, use of data and/or variables see files "Technical Report_V1" and "Codebook Variablen V1"
disclaimer: Even though the quality of the data is considered as relatively high, it cannot be ruled out that incorrect information has been provided in some cases. Therefore, caution should be exercised when presenting deviating results, in particular with regards to staffing levels of local administrations and state-related companies. Furthermore, the questionnaires were translated from German to French and Italian. Hence, it is possible that some of the questions might have been understood differently among the respondents from the different language regions. Misunderstandings can also not be ruled out completely with regards to certain technical terms. Depending on the level of knowledge or the degree to which a municipal secretary is affected by a specific topic, answering some of the questions could have been a challenge for some informants. These aspects must be considered when conducting data analyses.

This is an agreement (“Agreement”) between you the downloader (“Downloader”) and the owner of the materials (“User”) governing the use of the materials (“Materials”) to be downloaded. 
The Materials, as defined hereafter, have been acquired during the performance of the SILNE and SILNE-R H2020 projects entitled in full “Tackling socioeconomic inequalities in smoking: learning from natural experiments by time trend analyses and cross-national comparisons”.
The User, owners of the Materials are the consortium members of the SILNE and SILNE-R projects.

Materials 	
(Short description) 	The database includes data obtained during the performance of two social whole-network surveys in 67 secondary schools in Europe. It contains data obtained at different levels: at the student-level, at the school-level, at the dyad-level and finally a dataset at the staff-level.
The first survey (SILNE) aimed to analyse socio-economic inequalities in smoking among school-aged adolescents. In the second survey (SILNE-R) the implementation of school-tobacco control policies was a key objective.

Annex 1 : Data access rules and publication rules for SILNE survey (first and second wave) 
 
 
Revised, December 2018 
 
 
The aim of this document is to propose a general template for rules on data access and publication regarding the first and second wave of the SILNE-survey (survey coordinator Vincent Lorant) that have been creates in the SILNE and SILNE-R projects (project coordinator Anton Kunst). These are rules are not only meant to avoid dispute, but also to stimulate collaborative, comparative analyses. They are based on the rules that have been developed for the first wave of the SILNE survey.

A. General 
 
1. The WP leader and representatives of the seven countries (Belgium, Finland, Germany, Italy, The Netherlands, Portugal and Ireland) are called below “partners”. 
 
2. This agreement fully adheres to the SILNE-R Consortium Agreement (CA), including its articles on data ownership, data access rights, and dissemination. 
 
3. The agreement also takes into account the ethics requirements and data management rules specified for SILNE-R by the Horizon2020 program. 
 
4. This agreement assumes that partners adhere to existing rules on good scientific practice.  

B. Access to and use of SILNE data sets by partners 
 
5. The data of the seven countries are considered as one single data set, to be used for collaborative, international analyses.  
 
6. Data sets containing data from the 7 countries will be developed, maintained and upgraded by the WP leader.  
 
7. After validation and preliminary analyses, the WP leader will ensure a smooth transfer of relevant data sets, together with documentation, to other partners.  
 
8. The partners will not use the data sets for any other purposes than for research or feedback to respondents such as schools.

C. Access to and use of SILNE data sets by third parties 
 
9. “Third parties” include everyone not affiliated with the department (or other organizational units of similar size) of one of the partners.

10. Students at bachelors or masters levels may use the data for research, provided that they join the team of one of the partners and work at the partner’s premises. 
 
11. Before July 2020, partners will not give third parties access to the data unless agreed by all partners. Request to access the data will be decided by the “Publication Group” (see point 17 below).
